  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect through several key mechanisms:\n\n1. International Conventions and Treaties\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Establish global standards and expectations for anti-money laundering (AML) efforts\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries collaborate to investigate and prosecute cross-border money laundering\n- Sharing of financial intelligence and evidence\n- Extradition agreements\n\n3. Regulatory Standards\n- FATF sets global standards for national AML/CFT regulations\n- Countries implement consistent reporting and due diligence requirements\n- Promotes harmonization of legal frameworks\n\n4. Compliance Mechanisms\n- Banks and financial institutions must follow international and national AML regulations\n- Mandatory reporting of suspicious transactions\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n\n5. Enforcement Cooperation\n- International law enforcement agencies like Interpol\n- Coordinated investigations of complex money laundering schemes\n- Information sharing between national authorities\n\n6. Sanctions and Penalties\n- International sanctions against countries with weak AML frameworks\n- Potential financial and diplomatic consequences for non-compliance\n\nThese intersections create a comprehensive global approach to combating money laundering.",
